Africa Commuter Services may not be well known today. However if you go back 18 years to 2003, one of its planes that was carrying officials from the National Rainbow Coalition (NARC) after a celebration at then Vice President Moody Awori's home crashed on take off at the Busia airstrip. 

Labour Minister Ahmed Khalif and two pilots died following the accident while three other ministers Raphael Tuju (Tourism), Linah Kilimo (Office of the President) and Martha Karua (Water) were airlifted to Nairobi for treatment. 

As a reaction to the accident, the Transport Ministry canceled African Commuter Services operator's licence. The company immediately sued, leading to a lengthy 15-year legal battle that resulted in the State losing in 2018. Consequently taxpayers were made to pay Mr Jibril's company Sh1.3 billion for wrongful cancellation of its licence. 

While Mr Jibril was a laid back shrewd businessman who preferred doing his deals in the background, the person who Kenyans know is his famous brother Ahmed Jibril. In 2017, he stunned Nairobi’s super rich when he announced plans to put up a Sh1 billion hotel in the middle of Runda through one of his companies, Paddock Investments Limited. 



